Nice — then the next step should be locking this slice down before adding more features.

I would do it in this order:

1. Run final sanity tests

From the repo root:

python3 -m py_compile src/aerolitctl/server.py src/aerolitctl/cli.py

Then test the CLI wiring:

aerolitctl configure server --help
aerolitctl configure server --show
aerolitctl configure server --dry-run \
  --mode full \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.98.141 \
  --network 192.168.98.0/24 \
  --dhcp-start 192.168.98.150 \
  --dhcp-end 192.168.98.200 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.98.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin

Then confirm the real generated file still looks right:

cat /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml

And config:

cat /etc/aerolit/aerolitctl.yml

2. Commit this as one clean slice

This commit should be something like:

git status
git diff --stat
git add src/aerolitctl/server.py src/aerolitctl/cli.py
git commit -m "Add configure server CLI and guided planning"

Maybe include the path/config/doctor files too if those are part of this same MR:

git add src/aerolitctl/config.py src/aerolitctl/doctor.py src/aerolitctl/initialize.py src/aerolitctl/paths.py src/aerolitctl/server.py src/aerolitctl/cli.py
git commit -m "Add generated bootstrap vars under group_vars/all"

But I would not mix unrelated future deploy logic into this commit.

3. Next real feature slice

After this, the next logical slice is probably:

aerolitctl deploy server

or whatever command name you want, meaning:

configure server = write safe plan only
deploy server    = apply the plan

That deploy/apply command would eventually handle the stuff we intentionally did not let configure server do:

nmcli/interface IP setup
firewalld rules
NFS package/service/export setup
PXE HTTP/container/service setup
maybe restarting/reloading services

So the clean architecture becomes:

aerolitctl configure server
  writes:
    /etc/aerolit/aerolitctl.yml
    collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml
aerolitctl deploy server
  reads those values and applies system changes

I would make the next task not “make deploy server perfect.” I would start with a tiny safe skeleton:

aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run
aerolitctl deploy server --show-plan

Then add one apply area at a time: NFS first, firewall second, interface third, PXE last.